#chap-header("9", "Setting", "The World of Ash")

The world of Ashen is a ruin, but it is not dead. The cataclysm that the
histories call the Last War shattered the old order: it killed the gods, tore
wounds in the fabric of creation, and cursed the warriors who fought in it with
an immortality they did not ask for. From those wounds seeps the Fog --- the raw
power of creation, unbound and purposeless --- and it has swallowed most of the
world. Where the Fog is thin, mortals huddle in settlements called Clears, eking
out lives in the shadow of a broken sky. Where it is thick, nightmares breed and
the land itself shifts and writhes.

But Ashen is not a world without hope. The Deathless --- immortal veterans of the
Last War, cursed to walk until they lay their regrets to rest --- have organized
themselves into factions, each with its own vision of what the world should
become. They are explorers, warriors, scholars, and schemers. They are the
player characters, and the world's future is theirs to shape.

== History

=== The Age of Gods

In the beginning, there were the gods, and the world was theirs. The primordial
chaos settled into Vêr, the great sea, and Khanj, the dark sky, and from their
union came Khâru the Falcon-Headed Sun and Ndang the primordial land. The
children of Khâru and Ndang --- Night, Day, and their sister Order, called Third
--- were the first of the younger gods, and in time more followed.

The gods were not content merely to exist. They made peoples in their image, or
in images that pleased them. The Boar-Mother, great goddess of Life and Earth,
lay with the God of Crafts and bore the Humans, the first of the mortal races.
When she slew her lover in a jealous fury, it was Khâru who adopted the orphaned
race, and they have been torn between their divine parents ever since. The
Lion-Headed God of War, brother to the God of Crafts and jealous of him, pawned
his innocence to the Boar-Mother for children of his own: thus were the
Soot-Beasts born, creatures shaped for battle in body and temperament. The
Goddess Third, who loved toys and tinkers, gave life to the Clockworks, machines
of supreme elegance that walked and thought and fought. And far from the affairs
of the others, Day and Night --- better known in their fey aspects as Might-Be
and Once-Was --- built their own realms and filled them with the Echoes, fey
reflections of humanity seen through stranger lenses.

This was the Age of Gods: a time of direct divine rule, when the world was
shaped by will rather than chance, and the races lived under the watchful eyes of
their makers.

=== The Faerie Realms

Of all the works of the gods, the Faerie Realms were perhaps the most wondrous
and the most alien. The twin goddesses Might-Be and Once-Was --- known by many
names: Day and Night in the Boar-Mother's reckoning, the Fateweaver and the
Way-Knower among their own followers --- each carved out a domain that existed
alongside the material world, a reflection twisted by its creator's nature.

Might-Be's realm was one of beauty and caprice. She was the goddess of Magic,
Fate, and all things Resplendent, and her lands shifted with her moods: sunlit
meadows that could become labyrinths of crystal at a whim, courts of impossible
splendour where the price of a wrong word was a century of servitude. The
Mirrors, her favoured children, dwelt there as courtiers and tricksters, adept
at the arts of misdirection that their mother prized above all else.

Once-Was, by contrast, ruled in darkness and silence. She was the goddess of what
is Hidden and Forgotten, and her domain lay underground: vast palaces carved from
living stone, lit by phosphorescent fungi and the cold light of captured stars.
The Shades, her companions, were hunters and seekers of lost things, and they
rode out from the deep places to hunt in the long winter nights of Faerie. In an
earlier age, she had been worshipped as Came-To-Pass, an unerring huntress;
something changed her, and her old name fell out of use.

The Faerie Realms are gone now, destroyed in the Last War or perhaps simply
unmade when their creators fell. The Echoes that once inhabited them walk the
material world as refugees from a home that no longer exists, carrying within
themselves the last echoes of that strange and beautiful power.

=== The Last War

What the histories agree on is this: a great war engulfed the world, a conflict
so vast that it drew in the gods themselves. It was not a war of mortals alone
--- the divine powers took the field, and their servants and children fought
alongside them. The reasons for the war are disputed. Some texts speak of a
betrayal among the gods; others of an invasion from beyond the world's edges;
still others claim that the war was inevitable, the gods having sown the seeds of
their own destruction in the act of creation itself.

What is certain is the aftermath. The war tore wounds in the fabric of creation
--- not metaphorical wounds, but real rents in the substance of the world,
through which the raw power of creation now seeps as the Fog. The gods died, or
were so diminished as to be indistinguishable from dead. Their power survives
only in fragments: the reliquaries that the faithful carry, remnants of divine
essence that still respond to prayer but offer no guidance, no voice, no will.

The warriors who fought in the Last War were marked by it. Whether by curse,
by bargain, or by some consequence of exposure to the unmaking of creation, they
became the Deathless: immortal, but stripped of most of their memories, bound to
walk the world until they find release. They are the oldest living beings in
Ashen, and yet they remember almost nothing of the age they survived.

The end of the war is the great gap in the record. The final battles, the
decisive moments, the act or event that brought the conflict to its close --- all
of this is lost. The Deathless who lived through it remember nothing of those
last days. Written records from the period are fragmentary, contradictory, or
simply absent, as though something --- or someone --- excised the conclusion from
history. Whether this gap is the result of the cataclysm's own violence, a
deliberate act of concealment, or something stranger still, no one can say. It
is, by all accounts, the single most important unanswered question in the world.

=== The Age of Ash

In the aftermath of the Last War, the world did not so much recover as
stabilize. The Fog settled into patterns: dense in some regions, thin in
others, and where it receded, the first Clears emerged --- pockets of land where
mortal life could take root again. The Deathless, waking on the banks of rivers
or in the ruins of cities they no longer recognized, began to organize. Some
sought answers. Others sought power. Most sought purpose.

The factions that now dominate Deathless society were not founded in a single
moment but coalesced over the long years of the Age of Ash. Each represents a
different answer to the fundamental question that the Last War left behind: what
should the world become? Some factions seek to restore what was lost --- the
Faerie Realms, the rule of the gods, the cycle of death and rebirth. Others
accept that the old world is gone and work to build something new. A few believe
the world should be allowed --- or helped --- to end entirely.

Mortal civilizations, meanwhile, have grown in the shelter of the Clears. They
are younger than the factions, and largely dependent on them: the Deathless
provide protection, knowledge, and access to the old world's technology, and in
return they receive labour, loyalty, and the comfort of something to protect.
The relationship is not always benign. Some factions treat their mortal wards as
citizens; others, as resources.

The current age is one of uneasy equilibrium. The factions bicker and
occasionally skirmish, but no single group has the strength to impose its will on
the others. The Fog advances and retreats, and with it the fortunes of the
settlements that border it. The world is not healing, exactly, but it is not
dying either. It is waiting --- though for what, no one agrees.

== Cosmology

=== The Creation

The following text is the oldest known account of the world's origin. It is
translated from the _Âl i pHethkê yi Ndang_, a sacred work favored by the
devotees of the Boar-Mother, and is one of several creation narratives that
survive from the Age of Gods. While the broad strokes are consistent across
traditions, the details --- and especially the roles assigned to individual
deities --- vary considerably depending on the source.

#flavor[
  At the beginning, there was only the primordial chaos. In time, the chaos settled, and left at the bottom Vêr, the primordial sea, and Khanj, the dark sky. The sea and the sky resolved to each take on an aspect of the other, and from their strange union were born Khâru, the Falcon-Headed Sun, and Ndang, the primordial land. Khâru took the warmth from his mother's depths, but could not hold it in his lofty body; Ndang was great and profound, but took on her father's cold and stillness. Khâru's light and heat warmed the world, but made the sky to grow furious with wind, dried the sea and scorched the earth. When he saw what his unrestrained self had wrought, he resolved to sink beneath the waters for half his time, and thus did he establish order. From this union with his mother were born the sisters Night and Day, and the Third sister, known as Order.
]

=== The Pantheon

The gods of Ashen are dead, or so diminished that the distinction is academic.
Their power persists in reliquaries and in the lingering effects of their
creation, but they no longer speak, no longer intervene, and no longer answer
prayers with anything more than reflex. What follows is a summary of the
principal deities as they were understood before the Last War.

==== The Primordials

*Vêr*, the primordial sea, and *Khanj*, the dark sky, are the oldest entities
in the cosmology. They are not gods in the conventional sense --- they did not
create deliberately, but rather settled out of the chaos like sediment from
water. Whether they are conscious, or ever were, is a matter of theological
debate. They are not worshipped, but they are acknowledged: Vêr as the source
of all potential, Khanj as the boundary of all things.

==== The Major Gods

*Khâru*, the Falcon-Headed Sun, also called the Sun Life-Giver. God of light,
warmth, and the cycle of day and night. Father of humanity by adoption, after the
death of the God of Crafts. Khâru is remembered as a stern but generous patron:
demanding of his children, but willing to reward their efforts. His relics are
said to be gathered in the great library of the Seat of the Sun.

*The Boar-Mother*, goddess of Life, Earth, and the primal forces of nature.
Mother of humanity (with the God of Crafts) and of the Soot-Beasts (with the
Lion-Headed God of War). She is remembered as generous and terrible in equal
measure: one who gave freely, but who exacted obedience from those in her debt.
Her sacred text, the _Âl i pHethkê yi Ndang_, is the source of the oldest
surviving creation myth.

The Boar-Mother's domains are so vast that she is rarely venerated as a single
being, but rather worshipped in her three aspects -- the most popular with
mortals remains the *Spring Maiden*, goddess of youth and fertility, watching over
the young couple equally as she does the farmer sowing his seeds. The second aspect
is the *Winter Crone*, representing at once the uncaring cruelty of nature as well
as the tenacity to overcome it. She is the patron of the old praying for good health,
the farmer's storehouse, and the thrifty merchant. Finally, more feared than
worshipped, comes the *Beast* -- nature red in tooth and claw. Icons of this
boar-headed giant are few and far between, but his name is frequently invoked in
oaths, and Soot-Beast warriors have been known to take a liking to this forceful
deity.

*The God of Crafts*, whose name is now lost. Father of humanity, lover of the
Boar-Mother, slain by her in a jealous rage. Little survives of his worship,
and what does is fragmentary. He is remembered chiefly through the humans he
sired and the brother who envied him.

*The Lion-Headed God of War*, brother of the God of Crafts. A jealous god who
pawned his innocence to the Boar-Mother in exchange for children of his own ---
the Soot-Beasts. He is said to have been always itching for war, and his
creations reflect his temperament. In addition to his ancient association with battle,
the Lion-Head is co-patron (with Might-Be, the Queen of Summer)
of the Never-Still, who seek to restore the Faerie Realm.
His martial temperament complements the Queen's vitality: where she
dreams of renewal, he fights for it.

*The Goddess Third*, also called Order. Daughter of Khâru and Ndang and
youngest sister of Day and Night --- the goddesses better known in their fey
aspects as Might-Be and Once-Was. A goddess of artifice, craft, and the
imposition of order upon chaos, she is the patron of Arcane magic, the most
regular and predictable of the three magical disciplines, fit to be codified
and taught from books. She loved toys and tinkers, and when the Last War
came, her creations --- the Clockworks --- marched alongside her. The
Perfectors worship her memory and seek to continue her work.

*Might-Be*, the Fateweaver, Queen of Summer, also called the Glory Resplendent and, in the
Boar-Mother's sacred text, Day. Goddess of magic, fate, and beauty; twin to
Once-Was and elder sister to Third. She ruled the sunlit courts of Faerie and
created the Mirrors in her image. As the ultimate adjudicator of what might
be, she is the patron of Divine magic, and her authority is said to hold even
the other powers in check. Capricious and dazzling, she is remembered as much
for the wonders of her realm as for its cruelties.

*Once-Was*, the Way-Knower, called Night in the Boar-Mother's
reckoning, but known to her Shades as the *Midnight Princess*.
Goddess of what is Hidden and Forgotten; twin to Might-Be and elder
sister to Third. Formerly worshipped as *Came-To-Pass*, an unerring huntress,
before some unknown event changed her nature. She ruled the underground
palaces of Faerie and was companion to the Shades. Her domain is what was and
what might have been, and she is the patron of Psychic magic --- the
strangest of the three disciplines, and the one most given to bending what is
into what was not. Of all the gods, she is perhaps the most mysterious: even
the accounts that survive of her seem to conceal more than they reveal.

==== The Lesser Powers

The following beings are attested in various sources as objects of worship,
patrons of factions, or figures of theological significance. Whether they are
gods in the same sense as the major deities, or something else entirely ---
powerful spirits, ascended mortals, or personified forces --- is a question
without a settled answer.

*The Ferryman*, god of Death and Rebirth. Once a psychopomp, a guide of souls
between the world of the living and the underworld. In the Age of Ash, the
Ferryman is said to still ply the waters of the Kethû, fishing the essences of
newly awakened Deathless from its fog-shrouded currents. The Mortefactors revere
him.

*The Unsleeping*, the Lone Vigil, also called the Last Lamp and the Warden of
the Door. Patron of the Order of the Lantern, associated with vigilance,
guardianship, and the concept of escape. His followers believe the world in its
current state is a trap --- Purgatory --- and that the Unsleeping holds the key
to liberation.

*The Crown Lawgiver*, a god of law, order, and rightful dominion. Patron of the
Dragon Slayers, who interpret his doctrine as a mandate to make the world safe
for humanity under structured governance.

*The Moon Who-Reflects-In-Blood*, a goddess of the night, transformation, and
undeath. Patron of the Heirs of the Night. Her worship is closely associated with
vampirism and the creatures that thrive in darkness.

*The Queen of Silence*, a goddess of death, endings, and the quiet that follows.
Patron of the Brotherhood of the Silent Crow, who seek to restore the natural
cycle of death and rebirth that the Last War disrupted.

*She Who Waits Beyond*, a figure associated with finality and the end of all
things. Patron of the Witnesses of the End, who believe the world's destruction
was left incomplete and should be finished.

*The World Serpent*, a primordial being associated with life, poison, and the
deep forces of the earth. The western island chain is said to be its bones, and
the island of Dragon's Head its skull. Prayers to the World Serpent invoke its
power over vitality and venom.

=== The Nine Aspects

The magical traditions of Ashen recognize nine *Aspects*: fundamental forces or
principles that underlie creation. They are not gods, nor are they worshipped as
such, but they are the building blocks of ritual magic, and their influence
shapes the world in ways both subtle and profound.

- *Ash* --- destruction and desolation. The force of unmaking, of things reduced to their most basic state. Dominant in the wake of the Last War.
- *Crown* --- law and domination. The force of hierarchy, structure, and imposed order.
- *Forge* --- crafting, heat, and origin. The force of making and transformation through fire and will.
- *Key* --- opening and summoning. The force that bridges distances and draws things from one place to another.
- *Mist* --- magic and the sublime essence. The purest expression of the Fog's power, refined and directed.
- *Scarab* --- rebirth and cycles. The force of renewal, of death giving way to life, of patterns repeating.
- *Skull* --- death and the end of things. Not destruction (that is Ash), but the natural cessation that the Deathless are denied.
- *Moon* --- mind and matter. The force of thought, perception, and the strange relationship between consciousness and the physical world.
- *Maiden* --- nature. The force of growth, wildness, and the living world as it exists apart from the will of gods or mortals.

In ritual magic, the Aspects function as influences: a ritual's required Aspects
must be present in the environment or provided through sacrificed objects. At
higher tiers, the interplay of Aspects becomes critical, and the places where
particular Aspects concentrate --- leylines, ancient temples, sites of great
violence or great creation --- become strategically valuable.

=== Purgatory and the Curse of the Deathless

The Order of the Lantern calls the world _Purgatory_, and while not all factions
agree with the theology, the metaphor has stuck. The world as it exists is, in a
meaningful sense, a trap. The natural cycle of death and rebirth --- the passage
of souls from life through the underworld and back again --- was broken by the
Last War. Souls no longer pass on. The dead do not stay dead, and the living are
born into a world that was not meant to persist in its current form.

The Deathless are the most visible symptom of this break. They are souls that
cannot move on, bound to the world by regrets they can no longer fully remember.
Their curse grants them immortality --- when a Deathless dies, their essence
travels to a place they are bound to, their soul anchor, and slowly
reincorporates there over the course of days. But this immortality is a cage:
they cannot grow, cannot change, cannot find peace until they confront whatever
it is that holds them.

The factions, at their core, are different responses to this predicament. The
Mortefactors study the curse in hopes of understanding it. The Order of the
Lantern seeks to escape the trap entirely. The Brotherhood of the Silent Crow
wants to repair the cycle. The Witnesses of the End believe the only way out is
through --- that the world must be allowed to finish dying. And the rest, in
their own ways, are trying to build something worth living in while the question
remains unanswered.

== Geography

=== The Shape of the World

The world of Ashen is, to the best of anyone's knowledge, flat --- or at least
bounded. It behaves in many respects as though it were a sphere: the sun rises
and sets, the climate grows colder toward the north and warmer toward the south,
and there is a visible horizon. But those who have sailed too far from the
continent's shores report the same thing: the Fog thickens until it becomes an
impenetrable wall, and beyond that wall there is nothing, or at least nothing
that anyone has returned to describe.

There is one known continent, and one major island chain off its western coast.
If other lands exist beyond the Fog, no expedition has found them.

=== The Fog

The Fog is the defining feature of the world. It is the raw power of creation,
seeping from the wounds that the Last War tore in the fabric of reality. In the
old world, this power was shaped by divine will --- directed, purposeful,
the medium through which the gods worked their miracles. Now it is unbound: a
vast, ambient magical energy that saturates the world without intent or design.

The Fog varies in density. In the *Clears*, it is negligible --- thin enough
that the ambient magical energy is barely perceptible, and mortals can live and
work without ill effect. In areas of *Light Fog*, the air shimmers and strange
things can be glimpsed at the edges of vision; travel is possible but wary.
*Dense Fog* is dangerous: visibility drops, creatures born of the Fog appear
with alarming frequency, and the ambient energy is strong enough to power
magitek devices without external fuel. In zones of *Extreme Fog*, the world
itself becomes unreliable --- distances shift, time passes strangely, and
prolonged exposure warps both body and mind. The Fogborn, humans mutated by
generations of exposure, are living proof of its transformative power.

The Fog is not merely a hazard. It is also a resource. Magitek power plants
draw energy from Dense Fog, and the technology of the old world --- airships,
plasma weapons, and stranger things --- runs on the same ambient energy that
makes the Fog so dangerous. This tension --- between the Fog as threat and the
Fog as fuel --- shapes the politics and economy of the Age of Ash.

=== The Continent

The sole known landmass is dominated by a central mountain range that divides it
roughly into quarters: northwest, northeast, southwest, and southeast. A smaller
chain of mountains runs along the western coast, and another stretches into the
southeast. Between and beyond these ranges lie forests, deserts, river valleys,
and the scattered Clears where civilization persists.

The continent spans a wide range of climates: icy coasts in the far north,
dense subtropical forests in the northwest, arid wastes in the southwest, and
more temperate lands in the south and east. The Fog does not respect climate
boundaries --- a frozen tundra and a sweltering jungle may both be equally
choked with it --- but the Clears that form within each region take on the
character of their surroundings.

=== The Kethû

The great river known in the common tongue as the Kethû --- though it has as
many names as there are languages spoken along its banks --- flows from the
central mountains southward and westward, dividing the northwest from the
southwest. It is a zone of Extreme Fog along its entire length, and crossing it
is one of the most dangerous undertakings in the world.

The Kethû is no ordinary river. It is said to be the same watercourse that once
ran around the underworld, the boundary between the living and the dead. The
Ferryman, the god of Death and Rebirth, is said to still ply its fog-choked
waters, and many Deathless awaken for the first time on its banks --- as though
the Ferryman himself fishes their immortal essences from the current and deposits
them on the shore.

For all its danger, the Kethû is a landmark of immense strategic importance. The
settlements along its banks are among the oldest in the Age of Ash, and the
river's Extreme Fog makes it a natural barrier that has shaped the political
geography of the continent.

=== The Black Bazaar

On the southern banks of the Kethû lies the Black Bazaar: a small, artificial
Clear containing a market town. It is one of the few settlements in the world
that bars mortals from entry. Only the Deathless are permitted inside, and the
Bazaar serves as neutral ground for the factions --- a place where rivals can
trade, negotiate, and settle disputes without the threat of open warfare.

The Black Guard, a faction in its own right, watches over the Bazaar and serves
as a corps of arbiters for inter-faction disputes. Their authority within the
Bazaar's boundaries is absolute, and even the most powerful factions respect it
--- or at least find it prudent to appear to respect it.

=== The River Clear

On the northern banks of the Kethû, nestled against the foothills of the central
mountains, lies the River Clear: one of the largest Clears in the world. Its
size and its proximity to the Kethû's water supply make it extraordinarily
fertile, and it supports a large and prosperous mortal population.

The River Clear is divided into thirds, each controlled by a different faction:
the Dragon Guard, the Children of the Flame, and the Order of the Lantern. The
three factions bicker endlessly over resources, influence, and theology, but
outright conflict is rare --- the Clear is too valuable to risk damaging, and all
three know it. For most of its mortal inhabitants, the factional politics are a
distant irritation rather than a daily concern. Life in the River Clear is, by
the standards of the Age of Ash, remarkably comfortable.

=== The Northwest: Forests and Weald

West and north of the River Clear, the continent gives way to dense subtropical
forest. The canopy is thick enough to filter the Fog in places, creating pockets
of relative safety even outside the formal Clears, and the region supports a
surprisingly large population for its apparent wildness.

Several large Clears are scattered through the forest, the most notable of which
is *Venna Weald*. This is a major settlement divided between three factions ---
the Listeners, the Vatic Order of Patients, and the Never-Still --- who share
the territory in a complex arrangement that is part treaty, part tradition, and
part mutual suspicion. The Weald's proximity to old Faerie sites makes it
significant to all three factions: the Listeners seek to commune with the primal
spirits that linger there, the Patients cultivate the gift of clairvoyance that
the region's magical resonance seems to amplify, and the Never-Still believe the
Faerie Realms can be restored from exactly such places.

=== The North Coast

Beyond the forests, the continent's northern coast is icy, windswept, and
sparsely populated. Clears are few and far between, and those that exist tend to
be small, isolated, and fiercely independent.

The most notable settlement is the *Amkau Clear*, named after the largest river
that flows through it. It contains the town of *New Ko Vihya*, a modest but
well-defended community, and the ruins of *Old Ko Vihya*, which lie just outside
the Clear's boundaries. Old Ko Vihya was once the seat of an order of wizards
who practiced magic so reviled that the other Deathless factions --- normally
incapable of sustained cooperation --- banded together to destroy them. The
details of what the order did have been deliberately suppressed, but the name of
their leader, *Vay Ngien*, is still spoken with disgust. His ruined tower stands
on the north coast, outside the Clear, a monument to the one thing the factions
have ever agreed on.

=== The Northeast: The Forest of Night

The northeastern reaches of the continent are dominated by the *Forest of
Night*: an enormous expanse of woodland shrouded in permanent, magical darkness.
The darkness is not merely the absence of light but an active force, one that
resists torches, lanterns, and even magical illumination. Within it, the normal
cycle of day and night does not apply.

The Forest of Night is the domain of the *Heirs of the Night*, a faction
dedicated to the Moon Who-Reflects-In-Blood. It is a haven for vampires --- both
those who are merely undead, and those among the Heirs who bear the Deathless
curse as well, making them doubly immortal. For most mortals and many Deathless,
the Forest of Night is a place to be avoided. For the Heirs, it is a paradise in
the making.

=== The Southwest: The Sand Wastes

South of the Kethû, the continent's southwestern quarter is dominated by the
*Sand Wastes*: a vast desert that stretches nearly to the western coast. The heat
is brutal, water is scarce, and the Fog, while present, takes on a dry and
shimmering quality that is distinct from the damp miasma found elsewhere.

The Sand Wastes are rich in ruins. The dry heat has preserved relics of the Last
War --- weapons, fortifications, and stranger things --- in a state that the
damp and fog-choked regions of the continent cannot match. Expeditions into the
Wastes are a reliable source of old-world technology and a correspondingly
reliable way to die. The ruins are not unguarded: creatures born of the Fog
nest in them, and the desert itself is hostile to the unprepared.

=== The Southeast: The Seat of the Sun

The continent's southeastern quarter is home to the largest Clear in the world:
the *Seat of the Sun*. It is the closest thing the Age of Ash has to a great
civilization.

The Seat of the Sun is governed by the *Dragon Slayers, Most Fraternal and
Knightly Order of*, who rule not as kings but as a military order --- a
disciplined hierarchy of Deathless knights dedicated to the Crown Lawgiver and
the principle that the world should be made safe for humanity. Their governance
is efficient, if not always gentle, and the mortal population under their
protection is the largest and most prosperous on the continent.

The Seat is also the primary base of operations for the *Perfectors*, whose
workshops produce a disproportionate share of the world's remaining industrial
output. The alliance between the Dragon Slayers and the Perfectors is one of
convenience and mutual need: the Slayers provide order, labour, and protection;
the Perfectors provide the technology and infrastructure that makes the Seat
function.

The capital of the Seat of the Sun contains the largest library in the world
and, it is said, a vast collection of relics of the Sun God Khâru. Whether this
collection is a museum, a treasury, or a shrine depends on who you ask.

=== The Western Islands

Off the continent's western coast stretches a chain of islands nearly as long as
the continent is tall from north to south. The islands are said to be the
*bones of the World Serpent*, and the largest and northernmost of them is called
*Dragon's Head*.

Reaching the islands is perilous. The open sea between the continent and the
chain is a zone of Dense to Extreme Fog, and the crossing claims ships and
expeditions with grim regularity. Those who have made the journey and returned
speak of the islands as places of immense and unsettling power --- old places,
saturated with a magical energy that feels different from the Fog, more
purposeful, as though something vast and ancient were still alive beneath the
stone.

The islands are said to hold dark secrets. Whether they are worth the cost of
reaching them is a question that every generation of Deathless asks anew.

=== Magitek and Technology

The technology of the old world was a fusion of craft and magic that the current
age calls *magitek*. Airships, plasma weapons, powered armor, magnetic
accelerators, vehicles that hover on fields of arcane force --- all of these
existed before the Last War, and many survive in some form. But the secrets of
their construction are largely lost. What remains is scavenged, repaired,
reverse-engineered, and jealously hoarded.

The *Perfectors* are the primary custodians of industrial knowledge, and their
workshops in the Seat of the Sun are the closest thing the world has to
manufacturing. Elsewhere, technology is a matter of salvage: Deathless
expeditions into the Sand Wastes, the Fog-choked ruins of old cities, and other
dangerous places bring back components and devices that are then painstakingly
restored. Conventional firearms, at least, can be produced with current
knowledge --- they are a post-cataclysm development, crude by old-world
standards but reliable and widely available.

One of the more paradoxical features of magitek is its relationship with the
Fog. Devices equipped with harvesting technology can draw power directly from
Dense Fog, running indefinitely without external fuel. This makes the most
dangerous regions of the world also the most strategically valuable for those
with the technology to exploit them --- and it means that the Fog, for all its
horrors, is the engine that keeps what remains of civilization running.

==== Skimmers <skimmers>

The most common magitek vehicle is the *skimmer*: a craft that hovers on a
field of arcane force, typically a meter or so above the ground. Skimmers
range from single-seat racing frames to armored troop carriers the size of
a small building. They are fast, maneuverable, and relatively simple to
maintain --- a skimmer's lift array is one of the few pieces of old-world
technology that current artificers can reliably repair and even, in some
cases, build from scratch.

Skimmers cannot fly. Their lift fields interact with the ground beneath
them; take the ground away and the craft drops. A skimmer can clear
obstacles, skim over water, and handle rough terrain that would stop a
wheeled vehicle, but it cannot gain significant altitude. This makes them
ideal for overland travel and ground combat, but useless for crossing the
great chasms, mountain ranges, and ocean distances that divide the world's
Clears.

Military skimmers often mount weaponry: a pintle-mounted gun, a fixed
forward cannon, or in the case of heavier models, a turret. Armed
skimmers are the backbone of faction ground forces, filling the role that
armored vehicles occupy in conventional warfare. For rules on using
skimmers in combat, see #link(<vehicle-combat>)[_Vehicle Combat_] in the
Combat chapter.

==== Airships <airships>

Where skimmers hug the ground, *airships* command the sky. An airship
stays aloft through the same principle as a skimmer --- a reactor-powered
lift array --- but at vastly greater scale. A *Mist reactor* draws power
from ambient Fog to drive the lift array, feed the air-breathing turbine
engines that provide forward thrust, and supply electrical energy to the
vessel's onboard systems. The reactor is the heart of the vessel: without
it, most airships have no lift at all and fall like rocks. Some smaller
designs incorporate wings that reduce reactor fuel consumption during
cruising flight and allow the ship to glide to a rough landing if lift
is lost, but larger vessels have no such margin.

Mist reactors are old-world technology, and no one alive knows how to
build one from scratch. Every airship in the sky runs on a reactor
salvaged, repaired, or cannibalized from the ruins of the Last War. This
makes airships rare, irreplaceable, and strategically decisive. A faction
that controls even a single airship can project power across distances
that ground forces cannot hope to cover, and the loss of an airship is a
catastrophe measured in decades --- the time it takes to find and restore
a replacement reactor.

The size and role of airships vary enormously. The smallest are
single-reactor scout vessels, perhaps thirty meters long, crewed by a
dozen people, fast and lightly armed. The largest --- the great
dreadnoughts of the pre-war fleets --- are hundreds of meters long, carry
crews of hundreds, and mount weapons that can level a city block. Most
surviving airships fall somewhere in between: armed merchantmen, patrol
frigates, or expedition vessels refitted for the needs of the current
age.

Because Mist reactors draw power from the Fog, an airship's operational
range is effectively unlimited in Fog-covered regions. In Clears, where
the ambient Fog is thin or absent, a reactor must run on stored reserves,
limiting the vessel's endurance. This creates a strategic calculus:
airships are most powerful in the most dangerous parts of the world, and
most vulnerable in the safe ones. Long-range flights between distant
Clears require careful route planning through Fog corridors, and an
airship stranded in a Clear with depleted reserves is little more than a
very expensive target.

For the rules governing airship combat, see
#link(<vehicle-combat>)[_Vehicle Combat_] in the Combat chapter.

== Languages

The world of Ashen is not linguistically unified. Several major language
families are spoken across the continent, shaped by geography, the Fog, and the
long isolation of communities from one another. What follows is a summary of the
principal languages a traveller is likely to encounter.

=== Sarkat

The closest thing the world has to a common tongue is the Sarkat language ---
though, like many widely spoken languages, it is better understood as a large
family of closely related dialects than as a single uniform language. Sarkat
varieties are spoken from the far southeast to the west-central regions of the
continent, by Deathless, mortals, and Fogborn alike. Nearly all Deathless know
at least one variety of Sarkat.

The two prestige dialects are those of the *Seat of the Sun* (eastern Sarkat)
and the *River Clear* (western Sarkat). Despite their shared status, the two
belong to different dialect groups and are not immediately mutually intelligible
--- a source of endless frustration for travellers moving between the continent's
two great centres of civilization. Most names in this book are given in their
River Clear Sarkat form.

Some examples of Sarkat vocabulary: _Khanj_ is both the name of the primordial
sky and the common word for "sky" in this language. The sacred text _Âl i
pHethkê yi Ndang_ is titled in River Clear Sarkat --- though its original
version is assumed to have been composed in some now long-lost language --- and
translates simply to "Tale of the Creation of the Earth." To illustrate the
difference between the two Sarkat varieties, the word for sky in the Seat
of the Sun is _Khaj_ --- similar enough --- but the title of the Boar-Mother's
sacred text would be rendered as _Agalak Phethekanya Dag_.

The Fogborn who live around the Black Bazaar, separated from the River Clear by
the Extreme Fog of the Kethû, have developed a fairly divergent variety of their
own. Most Deathless visiting the Bazaar prefer to speak River Clear Sarkat with
one another regardless.

=== Inggiric

The Inggiric languages are spoken in the southwest and parts of the central west.
The eastern Inggiric dialects have significant contact with far western Sarkat
varieties, resulting in shared grammar and loanwords, but the two families are
fundamentally very different.

The Sand Wastes in particular are home to nomadic peoples who speak a
harsh-sounding, guttural variety they call *Leriel-e Inggir* --- "Speech of the
Sand Country." Some Inggiric place names include *Xen Waryd* (the Long Dune)
and *Yrr-a Xyndy* (Camp Khendi), a rare permanent settlement in an otherwise
nomadic culture. The legendary spirit *Iew-e Haxt*, Father of Sand, is also
named in this language.

=== Ngoay

In the northwest and along the frozen north coast, the Ngoay languages are
spoken. The people of the north have a reputation for being gruff, and their
languages --- built of short words and concise grammar --- only reinforce the
impression.

The name *Vay Ngien* is drawn from Ngoay. Rumour has it that the wizard used a
different, Sarkat name in his dealings with other Deathless, but this name has
been suppressed along with the rest of his order's legacy. The crumbling tower
outside the Amkau Clear is called *Ik Choa Vay Ngien* by the locals; an appellation
that combines the words for tower and fortress, and is used for no other structure.

Those who have managed the perilous crossing to Dragon's Head report that the
Fogborn who inhabit the island speak a highly divergent Ngoay variety. There are
rumours of a hidden fortress in the island's interior, called *Yeak Chô Thaw
Thêny*, or the Tower of Ridge Mountain, in the local dialect. Whether it is a
coincidence that they, too, call something a tower-fortress is anyone's guess.

=== Echo Languages

The Echoes, tight-knit and originally extraplanar as they are, speak their own
family of languages. In Clears dominated by Deathless Echoes, even mortal humans
have sometimes adopted these languages. While several smaller dialects exist, the
two prestige varieties are *Azal*, spoken by the Mirrors, and *Wiyan*, spoken by
the Shades.

It is common enough for an Echo to speak both that one can frequently hear a
Mirror address a Shade in Azal and receive a response in Wiyan --- a strange
display of ancestral pride that would look like a breakdown in communication to
an outsider but is, in practice, perfectly functional.

Some Echo words have been borrowed or calqued into other languages. The epithets
"Queen of Summer" and "Midnight Princess" for the goddesses of the Mirrors and
Shades, respectively, are translations from their languages: Might-Be is known
in Azal as _Yāndehten_, and Once-Was in Wiyan as _Innuwikšaya_ --- although the
nouns _Queen_ and _Princess_ were supplied by speakers of languages that require
the weight of nominals. The Echoes, for their part, are fond of using adjectives
without any explicit referent, and the names of their goddesses most literally
translate to _Summery_ and _Midnighty_.

=== Other Languages

Smaller language families and isolates are spoken in the northeast, the forests
of the central west, and various coastal regions. The Forest of Night is home to
its own linguistic traditions, though few outsiders have spent enough time there
to document them. The Soot-Beasts, for their part, are said to have languages of
their own that predate their contact with the other races, though most
Soot-Beasts encountered in the Clears speak Sarkat fluently.

== Factions

The Deathless are immortal, but they are not united. In the centuries since the
Last War, they have organized themselves into factions: orders, brotherhoods,
and loose alliances bound together by shared beliefs about what the world is and
what it should become. Most factions are aligned with the memory of a particular
deity, and their goals reflect that patron's domains and values.

Membership in a faction is voluntary but significant. A faction provides
purpose, community, and resources --- things that an immortal being with
fragmented memories and no natural death to look forward to desperately needs.
Leaving a faction is possible but rarely easy, and those who belong to no faction
at all --- the Free Agents --- are viewed with a mixture of respect and pity.

What follows is a description of the major factions of the Age of Ash.

=== The Order of the Lantern

#note[*Symbol:* A stylized lantern. *Patron:* The Unsleeping.]

The Order of the Lantern is built on a single, radical theological claim: the
world as it currently exists is *Purgatory*. Not a metaphor, not a poetic
description of suffering, but a literal state of spiritual imprisonment. The
Unsleeping, their patron, is believed to be a divine guardian who remained
behind when the other gods died --- not to rule, but to keep vigil, holding
open the possibility of escape for those with the wisdom to find the way.

The Lanterns, as they are commonly called, are scholars, mystics, and explorers.
They study the nature of the Fog, the mechanics of the Deathless curse, and the
structure of the world itself, seeking the cracks in the prison walls. They are
intensely interested in the lost conclusion of the Last War, believing that the
answer to what happened at the end may also be the key to escape.

The Order controls a third of the River Clear, where it maintains extensive
archives and research facilities. Its members are often encountered in the
field, investigating anomalies in the Fog, exploring ruins for clues about the
old world, or following up on reports of anything that seems to violate the
normal rules of reality. They are generally well-regarded by other factions ---
their goals are abstract enough not to threaten anyone directly --- but their
willingness to probe the fundamental nature of the world makes some uneasy.

=== The Most Ancient and Noble Order of Mortefactors

#note[*Symbol:* A crossed scythe and bird wing under a human skull. *Patron:* The Ferryman.]

The Mortefactors are, by their own account, the oldest continuous faction in the
Age of Ash. They are dedicated to the study of the Deathless curse: its
mechanics, its origins, its variations, and --- they hope --- its cure. Where the
Order of the Lantern asks _why is the world a prison?_, the Mortefactors ask
_why can we not die?_

Their work is part medical, part theological, and part detective work. They
catalogue the experiences of Deathless across the world, seeking patterns in how
the curse manifests: what triggers awakening, what determines the location of a
soul anchor, whether the fragmented memories of the Deathless follow any
discernible logic. They maintain the most comprehensive records of individual
Deathless that exist --- a library of identities, many of them belonging to
people who have long since forgotten themselves.

The Ferryman, their patron, occupies a unique position among the lesser powers:
he is, by most accounts, still active. The Mortefactors' relationship with him
is not one of worship so much as professional respect --- he does his work, and
they do theirs, and occasionally the two intersect when a newly awakened
Deathless is pulled from the waters of the Kethû.

The Mortefactors are widely respected but not widely loved. Their work requires
a clinical detachment that many find unsettling, and their archives contain
secrets that some Deathless would prefer to remain forgotten.

=== The Most Fraternal and Knightly Order of Dragon Slayers

#note[*Symbol:* A dragon impaled upon a spear. *Patron:* The Crown Lawgiver.]

The Dragon Slayers are the largest and most powerful faction in the Age of Ash,
and the closest thing the world has to a legitimate government. From their seat
in the Seat of the Sun, they govern the largest Clear on the continent, command
the largest mortal population, and project military power across a wider area
than any other faction.

Their stated purpose --- making the world safe for humans --- is
straightforward, and they pursue it with the organized efficiency of the military
order they are. The Dragon Slayers build roads, patrol trade routes, clear Fog
incursions, and maintain the infrastructure that keeps mortal civilization
functioning. They are, in the eyes of many mortals, the heroes of the Age of
Ash.

The truth is more complicated. The Dragon Slayers are not merely protectors but
rulers, and their vision of a safe world is one in which humanity lives under
the structured governance of Deathless knights who know best. Their patron, the
Crown Lawgiver, is a god of law and rightful dominion, and the Slayers interpret
this as a mandate: order must be imposed, and they are the ones to impose it.
This puts them at odds with factions that prize freedom, secrecy, or any vision
of the world that does not place humanity --- and its Deathless guardians --- at
the centre.

Their name is something of an anachronism. The original Dragon Slayers were
founded to combat the great wyrms that terrorized the early Age of Ash, and
they earned their reputation in that crucible. The dragons are mostly gone now,
but the name --- and the martial culture it represents --- endures.

=== The Keepers of the Door

#note[*Symbol:* Two keys crossed over a gate. *Patron:* Once-Was Way-Knower.]

The Keepers of the Door are, by design, the faction that other factions know the
least about. They are dedicated to the discovery and safeguarding of secrets:
knowledge that is hidden, forbidden, or simply forgotten, collected and preserved
against the day it might be needed.

Their patron, Once-Was, was the goddess of what is Hidden and Forgotten --- a
fitting choice for an order that operates largely in the shadows. The Keepers
maintain a network of agents, informants, and hidden caches across the
continent, and they are said to know things about every other faction that those
factions would rather keep private. Whether this makes them the world's best
intelligence service or its most dangerous blackmailers depends on perspective.

The Keepers are particularly interested in the blank spaces of history: the lost
conclusion of the Last War, the suppressed records of Old Ko Vihya, the true
nature of the Western Islands, and any number of smaller mysteries that the other
factions have either overlooked or deliberately ignored. They do not share what
they find freely, but they can sometimes be persuaded --- for a price, or in
exchange for secrets of equal value.

For Game Masters, the Keepers of the Door are an invaluable source of plot
hooks. They are the faction most likely to approach the players with a strange
job, a cryptic warning, or a piece of information that changes everything.

=== The Perfectors

#note[*Symbol:* A bridge built of gears. *Patron:* Third.]

The Perfectors worship the memory of the Goddess Third and seek to continue her
work: the imposition of rational order upon a chaotic world, through the medium
of technology. They are engineers, artificers, and industrialists, and their
workshops in the Seat of the Sun produce the majority of the world's manufactured
goods.

The Perfectors' vision is not merely practical but philosophical. They believe
that the world broke because it was insufficiently ordered --- that the gods,
for all their power, were too capricious, too emotional, too _alive_ to build
something that would last. The solution, in their view, is a world governed by
mechanical precision: predictable, efficient, and free of the divine caprice
that led to the Last War. It is an ideology that appeals most strongly to the
Clockworks, many of whom see in the Perfectors a reflection of their own nature.

In practice, the Perfectors are indispensable. They maintain the magitek
infrastructure that the Seat of the Sun depends on, they repair and
reverse-engineer the old-world technology that other factions recover, and they
are the primary source of new innovations --- modest ones, by old-world
standards, but significant in an age of salvage and decline. Their alliance with
the Dragon Slayers is the backbone of the largest civilization in the world.

Their weakness is a certain rigidity of thought. The Perfectors are deeply
suspicious of magic that cannot be systematized, of divine power that does not
follow rules, and of anything that smacks of the chaotic fey traditions. This
puts them at odds with the Listeners, the Never-Still, and anyone else who
believes that the world's salvation lies in something other than gears and
logic.

=== Other Factions

*The Black Guard* maintain and police the Black Bazaar. They serve as arbiters
of inter-faction disputes within its walls, and their neutrality --- enforced by
a willingness to bar any faction that breaks the peace --- makes them the
closest thing the Deathless have to an impartial judiciary.

*The Children of the Flame* are dedicated to maintaining and expanding the
Clears. Aligned with the Sun Life-Giver, they are the faction most directly
responsible for pushing back the Fog and creating safe spaces for mortal
habitation. Their work is unglamorous but essential, and they are well-regarded
by the mortal populations they protect.

*The Dragon Guard* seek to restore a world fit for dragons. Where the Dragon
Slayers hunted the great wyrms, the Dragon Guard revered them, and they believe
that the return of the dragons is the key to the world's restoration. They are
aligned with Vrtra Dragon-Father and are, understandably, not on good terms with
the Dragon Slayers.

*The Heirs of the Night* serve the Moon Who-Reflects-In-Blood and seek to
make the world a paradise for creatures of the night. They dwell in the Forest of
Night and are closely associated with vampirism. Other factions regard them with
a mixture of wariness and pragmatic tolerance.

*The Listeners* seek to restore the Boar-Mother and the primal spirits of
the natural world. They are animists and spiritualists, attuned to the lingering
echoes of divine power in wild places, and they maintain a strong presence in
the forests of the northwest.

#colbreak()

*The Never-Still* are dedicated to restoring the vitality of the Faerie Realm.
Aligned with both the Lion-Head and the Might-Be Queen of Summer, they believe that the
fey domains can be rebuilt and that doing so is essential to healing the world.
They are dreamers and idealists in a world that has little patience for either.

*The Vatic Order of Patients* cultivate the art of clairvoyance under the
patronage of the Glory Resplendent, the Might-Be Fateweaver. They are seers and
oracles, and their readings --- while not always reliable --- are sought after by
those who wish to glimpse what is to come.

*The Brotherhood of the Silent Crow* serve the Queen of Silence and seek to
restore the cycle of death and rebirth. They are, in a sense, the Mortefactors'
theological cousins, but where the Mortefactors study the curse of the Deathless
with clinical detachment, the Silent Crows approach the broken cycle as a
spiritual wound that demands healing through devotion and ritual.

*The Waiting Fangs* are a faction whose stated purpose is simply self-defence.
They are secretive, pragmatic, and widely suspected of being rather more
aggressive than they claim. Their true agenda, if they have one, is not public
knowledge.

*The Witnesses of the End* believe that the ending of the world was left
incomplete and should be finished. Aligned with She Who Waits Beyond, they are
the most feared and least trusted of the factions --- not because they are
necessarily hostile, but because their ultimate goal is the annihilation of
everything that exists. Whether they are nihilists, mercy-killers, or something
stranger is a matter of considerable debate.

*Free Agents* are Deathless who belong to no faction. Some are former members of
other orders who left or were expelled; others never joined in the first place.
They are respected for their independence and pitied for their isolation. In a
world where purpose is the only thing standing between an immortal and madness,
going it alone is either very brave or very foolish.

